Progress in medicine depends on the transparency and openness of medical research. Journal policies can encourage authors to pre-register their protocol, share data and code, report results in full and make research practices open and transparent beyond a published article. The Centre for Open Science (COS) developed the Transparency and Openness Promotion (TOP) guideline in 2015 to encourage and improve the policies of journals (Nosek et al., 2015: https://science.sciencemag.org/content/348/6242/1422). The TOP guideline has eight standards:
data citation; 
data transparency;
analytical methods; 
research materials;
design and analysis;
study preregistration; 
analysis plan pre-registration; and
replication

Each standard is graded based on increasing levels of engagement: disclosure, requirement, and verification (more details here). Previous research using the TOP guideline has evaluated the policies of pain journals (Cashin et al., 2020: https://ebm.bmj.com/content/early/2020/01/24/bmjebm-2019-111296) which found limited engagement with transparent and open science standards. This is concerning because opaque scientific practices can result in unnecessary costs, slow scientific progress and may put patients' lives in danger. The policies of health and medical science journals have not been evaluated. 

Purpose: To evaluate high-ranking medical and health science journal policies on transparent and open science practices and inform journal editors of identified deficiencies. 

Research questions
With regards to high-ranking medical and health journals:
What is the degree of engagement with transparent and open science standards according to the COS scorecard for the TOP guideline? 
What are the requirements for disclosure of conflicts of interest using the International Committee of Medical Journal Editors (ICMJE) standard?

